# .trivyignore - Trivy security scanner configuration
# Manages false positives and known acceptable risks
# Format: CVE-ID or vulnerability rule pattern per line

# Development and Test Certificate Files
# These are test certificates used for development/testing mTLS functionality
# They are not used in production and are safe to ignore for security scanning

# Specific test certificate files to ignore
features/controller/certs/244812452512842577549117018372747127309/key.pem
features/controller/certs/ca/ca.key

# Development dependencies (test/build tools)
# These vulnerabilities are not exploitable in production deployment
# since test and build dependencies are not included in runtime binaries

# Go module dependencies - test-only packages
# Test packages are not included in production builds
# Uncomment specific CVEs below if they appear in test dependencies:
# CVE-XXXX-XXXXX  # Example: test dependency vulnerability

# Documentation and example files
# These files are not part of the production system
docs/
examples/
test/
*.md

# Configuration and template files that may contain patterns detected as secrets
# These are template files and documentation, not actual secrets
docs/examples/
docs/templates/

# Build artifacts and generated files
bin/
dist/
*.log
.git/

# IDE and editor files
.vscode/
.idea/
*.swp
*.swo
*~

# OS generated files
.DS_Store
Thumbs.db

# Common false positives in Go projects:
# Uncomment specific patterns if they become problematic:

# Generic passwords in test files (these are not real credentials)
# password
# secret
# token

# Example configuration files with placeholder values
# example.yaml
# sample.conf

# Note: This file should be reviewed regularly and updated as needed
# Each ignored item should have a justification comment explaining why it's safe to ignore